a, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bentley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places, the chief of which are in Derbyshire, Essex, Hampshire, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Suffolk, Warwickshire, Worcestershire, and East and South Yorkshire. The placename is from Old English <i>beonet</i> ‘bent grass’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","In some cases also an Americanized form of South German   Bentele   or of its Swiss German or South German cognates <b>Bandle</b> and <b>Bandli</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Bently","meanings":["English: variant of   Bentley   1.","Variant of   Bentley   2, a surname of South German or Swiss German origin."]},{"name":"Bentele","meanings":["(2010: NA)","South German: from a short form of the personal name <i>Pantaleon</i> (see   Pantaleo  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":11,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":20,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":55,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert De Bentley was born about 1204, in Bentley, Yorkshire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with Robert Bently."},"et":{"about 1204–":"umbes 1204–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1226–1315":"1226–1315","1204–Female":"1204–Surnud","1315":"1315","1226":"1226","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","1224":"1224","about 1204":"umbes 1204","1200":"1200","Bentley, Yorkshire, England":"Bentley, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1204–":"noin 1204–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1226–1315":"1226–1315","1204–Female":"1204–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1226":"1226","1259":"1259","1215":"1